<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f966546160415>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=1&mid=966546160415>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=1&mid=966546160415>Starting warrior advice</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=1&mid=966546160415#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Aug 17th 5:02 PM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=397><span id= >Squalus</span></a><br><span id=notbold>4 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.76]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Put one training point into Taunt first thing upon starting, at your guild<br>trainer. Unlike *every other skill in the game* your Taunt will never go<br>up, though it is one of the skills you start with at level 1, if you do not<br>spend at least one training point in it first. (most skills you gain access<br>to after level 1, will also require at least one training point be spent on<br>them, before you can advance it them, but Taunt is the only one that<br>requires this right from level 1)<br><br>Practice with all the weapon types available to you, whenever you can.<br>If you max out your skill (for your level) in one type, switch to another.<br>Does not matter what you use at first, even rusty weapons will do the<br>job. It is difficult to raise these later on, and far easier if you start early.<br>This includes 1/2handed blunt, 1/2handed slash, piercing, kick, and bash.<br><br>Take up fletching. HIGHLY recommended. The bow is a warriors best tool<br>for pulling monsters, and making your own arrows is highly cost efficient<br>over buying them. Of course, finding a fletching kit is always a pain, but<br>once you do, it is a simple matter to raise your skill up enough that basic<br>arrows are trivial to make. And the kit itself makes a decent pack.<br><br>If you see a mage with free time, ask if you can borrow a few summoned<br>bandages. I have received good responses from this, most mages seem<br>more then willing to help out. (sometimes getting 100+ at one shot!)<br>Then practice your bind wounds skill, alot. On yourself, on others. Practice,<br>practice, practice. The bandages are summoned, so will disappear as<br>soon as you log out (or go LD), so use them while you can. Bind Wounds <br>is the only option warriors have for healing themselves, and the skill<br>maxes out at 100 (though might go higher once you get to level 51+).<br>But still, 25 hit points per use, and only allowing you to get to half your<br>life bar, is better then sitting on your behind waiting for the same thing.<br><br></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
